Subject:    <a href="?t=95837887100039&r=1&w=2">Re: Query on fate of host nicknames</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837693200009&r=1&w=2">Mary Stahl &lt;STAHL () SRI-NIC ! ARPA&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198507">1985-07-11 18:23:03</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426512&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426512&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

Rich,


(1) As far as we know the dates specified in RFC 921 are still valid,
though somewhat unrealistic.

The phaseout date of September 15 refers to use of a flat HOSTS.TXT
table by the DARPA Internet community.  The NIC will continue
indefinitely to produce a host table for use by the DDN operational
community until a domain plan for them is fully inplemented and
supported.  When the DARPA domain system is in place and stable, we
will have developed software to query all the domain name servers in
the DARPA Internet so that a flat HOSTS.TXT table can be compiled from
the information gathered.  Until then we will continue to maintain the
host information (by hand, so to speak) in the NIC database.  There
are no plans to change the format of the table.

(2) When a host joins a domain, it no longer appears in the ARPA zone
files.  It will only appear in the zone file for its new domain.

(3) The non-domain nicknames currently listed in the host table will
not be entered into the domain database files, and there should be no
domain nicknames in the HOSTS.TXT table.  Responsibility for that
information is delegated to the maintainers of the domains.

Hosts should be using only official names, not nicknames, in their
mail headers.


- Mary Stahl
